Graphing Example

For these examples, we use several built-in data sets that can be accessed using the data() function.

1 Base Graphics Options

USArrests data contains statistics, in arrests per 100,000 residents for assault, murder, and rape in each of the 50 US states in 1973. Also given is the percent of the population living in urban areas.

data(USArrests)
str(USArrests)
## 'data.frame':    50 obs. of  4 variables:
##  $ Murder  : num  13.2 10 8.1 8.8 9 7.9 3.3 5.9 15.4 17.4 ...
##  $ Assault : int  236 263 294 190 276 204 110 238 335 211 ...
##  $ UrbanPop: int  58 48 80 50 91 78 77 72 80 60 ...
##  $ Rape    : num  21.2 44.5 31 19.5 40.6 38.7 11.1 15.8 31.9 25.8 ...
#Basic Scatterplot
plot(Murder ~ Assault, data = USArrests)

#Equivalent to:
#plot(USArrests$Assault, USArrests$Murder)
#Using Options
plot(Murder ~ Assault, data = USArrests, 
     pch = 16, col = "blue", 
     xlim = c(0, 400), ylim = c(0, 20), 
     xlab = "Assaults (per 100,000 residents)", 
     ylab = "Murders (per 100,000 residents)", 
     main="Scatterplot of Murder vs Assault")
abline(lm(Murder ~ Assault, data = USArrests), col = "red")
legend(0, 20, lty = 1, col = "red", c("LS fit"))

#Using Text
plot(Murder ~ Assault, data = USArrests, 
     type = "n", xlab = "Assault", ylab = "Murder", 
     main = "Scatterplot of Murder vs Assault")
text(Murder ~ Assault, data = USArrests, 
     labels = row.names(USArrests), cex = 0.5)

2 ggplot2 Package

2.1 USArrests

library(tidyverse)
qplot(Assault, Murder, data = USArrests)

#Equivalent to
#ggplot(USArrests,aes(x = Assault, y = Murder )) + 
#  geom_point()
#Adding Layers
qplot(Assault, Murder, size = UrbanPop, data = USArrests) +   
  geom_smooth(method = lm, size = 1, color = "red") + 
  labs( x = "Assaults (per 100,000 residents)",  
        y = "Murders (per 100,000 residents)",  
        size = "Urban Population (%)") +
  ggtitle("Scatterplot of Murder vs Assault")

2.2 Iris Data

iris data gives the measurements in centimeters of the variables sepal length and width and petal length and width, respectively, for 50 flowers from each of 3 species of iris. The species are Iris setosa, versicolor, and virginica.

qplot(Sepal.Length, Sepal.Width, shape = Species, data = iris)

qplot(Sepal.Length, Sepal.Width, color = Species, data = iris)

qplot(Sepal.Length, Sepal.Width, data = iris) +
  facet_grid(. ~ Species)

qplot(Sepal.Length, data = iris)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

qplot(Sepal.Length, fill = Species, data = iris)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

qplot(Sepal.Length, data = iris) +
  facet_grid(Species ~ .)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

2.3 Grouped Bar Chart

ToothGrowth data: The response is the length of odontoblasts (teeth) in each of 10 guinea pigs at each of three dose levels of Vitamin C (0.5, 1, and 2 mg) with each of two delivery methods (orange juice or ascorbic acid).

data(ToothGrowth)
str(ToothGrowth)
## 'data.frame':    60 obs. of  3 variables:
##  $ len : num  4.2 11.5 7.3 5.8 6.4 10 11.2 11.2 5.2 7 ...
##  $ supp: Factor w/ 2 levels "OJ","VC": 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 ...
##  $ dose: num  0.5 0.5 0.5 0.5 0.5 0.5 0.5 0.5 0.5 0.5 ...
# Use dose as a factor rather than numeric
ToothGrowth$dose <- as.factor(ToothGrowth$dose)
SumStats <- ToothGrowth %>%
            group_by(supp, dose) %>%
            summarise(n = n(),
                      mean = mean(len),
                      sd = sd(len),
                      se = sd/sqrt(n) )
SumStats
## # A tibble: 6 x 6
## # Groups:   supp [2]
##   supp  dose      n  mean    sd    se
##   <fct> <fct> <int> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 OJ    0.5      10 13.2   4.46 1.41 
## 2 OJ    1        10 22.7   3.91 1.24 
## 3 OJ    2        10 26.1   2.66 0.840
## 4 VC    0.5      10  7.98  2.75 0.869
## 5 VC    1        10 16.8   2.52 0.795
## 6 VC    2        10 26.1   4.80 1.52
ggplot(SumStats, aes(x = dose, y = mean, fill = supp)) + 
    geom_bar(position = position_dodge(), stat = "identity") +
    geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = mean-se, ymax = mean+se),
                  width=.2,  # Width of the error bars
                  position=position_dodge(.9))
